00:13:17,892 --> 00:13:20,150
I'm sure even the American
can appreciate

260
00:13:20,213 --> 00:13:22,314
the Honda's
hi-tech features.

261
00:13:22,799 --> 00:13:25,158
What is this
Space Invaders shit?

262
00:13:25,353 --> 00:13:26,767
Clearly not.

263
00:13:26,885 --> 00:13:29,742
Right, full power
for the Isn't again.

264
00:13:30,392 --> 00:13:33,392
Electric ain't for engines.
It's for lights and chairs.

265
00:13:33,861 --> 00:13:36,183
He is not a modern man, is he?

266
00:13:36,249 --> 00:13:38,705
Right, carving through
the standing water.

267
00:13:38,775 --> 00:13:40,588
Into Old Lady's House.

268
00:13:40,782 --> 00:13:42,439
Slithering about a bit.

269
00:13:42,525 --> 00:13:46,010
And now, he's leaning on it
for the Unsettled section.

270
00:13:46,119 --> 00:13:48,853
Past the hangars
and up to Sub Station.

271
00:13:49,174 --> 00:13:50,964
Hard on those wi-fi brakes

272
00:13:51,031 --> 00:13:52,924
for the second-to-last corner.

273
00:13:53,142 --> 00:13:55,189
How's he gonna manage
through here?

274
00:13:55,338 --> 00:13:57,689
Yes, stepping out a bit
under power.

275
00:13:57,830 --> 00:13:58,955
Through Field Of Sheep,

276
00:13:59,017 --> 00:14:01,315
keeping it tidy through
there, and across the line!

277
00:14:11,002 --> 00:14:12,572
Right,

278
00:14:13,509 --> 00:14:17,587
let's see now where the NSX
goes on our lap board.

279
00:14:17,666 --> 00:14:19,192
Let's have a look.

280
00:14:22,610 --> 00:14:24,879
- Oh.
- Oh, dear, James.

281
00:14:29,148 --> 00:14:30,449
James.

282
00:14:32,605 --> 00:14:34,908
Why didn't you tell us
it was very slow?

283
00:14:35,134 --> 00:14:38,166
- It's streaming wet!
- So hang on a minute.

284
00:14:38,191 --> 00:14:41,650
We've had a review from
a tortoise and a wet lap.

285
00:14:41,713 --> 00:14:44,322
Which means we've
learnt precisely nothing.

286
00:14:44,744 --> 00:14:45,830
Um...

287
00:14:45,892 --> 00:14:47,275
Yeah, you're right.
Nothing at all.

288
00:14:47,314 --> 00:14:48,963
- Nothing at all.
- So let's move on.

289
00:14:49,001 --> 00:14:50,766
Yes, let's do that, let's do that

290
00:14:50,800 --> 00:14:53,314
by popping some loose change
in the ticket machine

291
00:14:53,416 --> 00:14:56,885
so we can park awhile
on Conversation Street.

292
00:14:59,023 --> 00:15:02,486
♪♪

293
00:15:04,752 --> 00:15:06,760
OK, now...

294
00:15:06,930 --> 00:15:09,492
- I've got some conversation... Good
- Good.

295
00:15:09,666 --> 00:15:13,314
Last night at midnight,
there was alarm... in Stuttgart.

296
00:15:13,455 --> 00:15:15,627
The Green Party
that runs the city

297
00:15:15,720 --> 00:15:20,314
asked everyone here not to
use wood-burning stoves

298
00:15:20,447 --> 00:15:22,965
and not to drive
their car today.

299
00:15:23,166 --> 00:15:26,088
- Why?
- Because of the smog.

300
00:15:30,525 --> 00:15:32,365
Am I making this up?

301
00:15:32,807 --> 00:15:34,267
There it is.

302
00:15:38,771 --> 00:15:40,507
I can't...

303
00:15:40,751 --> 00:15:42,846
I can't imagine
anything clearer.

304
00:15:42,986 --> 00:15:45,275
That is... That is gin-clear,

305
00:15:45,337 --> 00:15:46,540
but according to
the Green Party...

306
00:15:46,564 --> 00:15:47,760
I'm not making this up.

307
00:15:47,785 --> 00:15:49,127
You're all from Stuttgart, yes?

308
00:15:49,213 --> 00:15:51,150
There is an alarm today

309
00:15:51,478 --> 00:15:53,416
- because of the smog.
- Yes.

310
00:15:54,244 --> 00:15:55,338
Where is it?

311
00:15:55,470 --> 00:15:58,681
- How clear is it on a good day?
- I like.

312
00:15:58,990 --> 00:16:02,565
Ah! Just, we've got a photograph here
of Beijing on now. -

313
00:16:03,056 --> 00:16:04,970
Let us compare and contrast

314
00:16:05,064 --> 00:16:08,002
Beijing on a smoggy day
with Stuttgart on a...

315
00:16:08,244 --> 00:16:09,869
- Not the same.
- a smoggy day.

316
00:16:09,936 --> 00:16:12,541
Can I just ask,
what would you have done

317
00:16:12,681 --> 00:16:15,181
if they'd have actually ordered
you not to drive cars?

318
00:16:15,212 --> 00:16:16,728
You know, at the moment,
it's an advisory.

319
00:16:16,752 --> 00:16:18,806
If they said you are
banned from driving cars,

320
00:16:18,908 --> 00:16:20,720
what would you have done?

321
00:16:21,103 --> 00:16:23,744
Come on the train?
That's unbelievable.

322
00:16:23,769 --> 00:16:24,978
But this is the thing

323
00:16:25,056 --> 00:16:26,673
that we don't really
understand about Germany.

324
00:16:26,697 --> 00:16:29,056
Once something becomes
a rule, it is a rule.

325
00:16:29,122 --> 00:16:31,556
I once had a very
interesting conversation

326
00:16:31,581 --> 00:16:32,469
with two friends of mine.

327
00:16:32,494 --> 00:16:35,064
One is from California
and one is from Germany.

328
00:16:35,220 --> 00:16:37,537
We were talking about
losing your driving licence.

329
00:16:37,767 --> 00:16:40,877
The Californian said, "In
Germany, what would happen"

330
00:16:40,916 --> 00:16:43,705
if you lost your licence
and then you drove your car?"

331
00:16:43,830 --> 00:16:45,738
The German said,
"No, you cannot do this."

332
00:16:47,557 --> 00:16:50,244
And he says, "I know
you're not supposed to",

333
00:16:50,283 --> 00:16:51,611
but what if you did?"

334
00:16:51,689 --> 00:16:54,306
He said, "No. You cannot
drive. You have no licence."

335
00:16:55,900 --> 00:16:57,157
The Californian
went, "Yeah, man",

336
00:16:57,181 --> 00:16:58,908
"but late one night, you just...

337
00:16:59,010 --> 00:17:00,400
hell, you go for a drive."

338
00:17:00,439 --> 00:17:02,119
The German went,
"It is impossible

339
00:17:02,150 --> 00:17:03,744
to drive without a licence!"

340
00:17:03,822 --> 00:17:06,439
- Impossible!
- Impossible.

341
00:17:11,650 --> 00:17:13,829
Actually, there's an interesting thing
I discovered here.

342
00:17:13,853 --> 00:17:17,595
On a motorway, okay, obviously you
can drive as fast as you like.

343
00:17:17,649 --> 00:17:19,142
You get people
sometimes, not often,

344
00:17:19,252 --> 00:17:20,963
cos your lane discipline
is unbelievable,

345
00:17:21,064 --> 00:17:24,564
but sometimes they sit in the
outside lane just dawdling.

346
00:17:24,705 --> 00:17:28,369
If you tailgate them... OK?
I've got the fines here.

347
00:17:28,424 --> 00:17:32,197
You get a 400 Euro fine,
two penalty points,

348
00:17:32,267 --> 00:17:35,002
and a three-month ban
for tailgating.

349
00:17:35,103 --> 00:17:36,588
- That is extreme. Ouch!
- Yes.

350
00:17:36,729 --> 00:17:38,807
But-But if you overtake them
on the inside,

351
00:17:38,908 --> 00:17:40,588
just go past them on the inside,

352
00:17:40,635 --> 00:17:43,705
that's a 150 Euro fine,
and one point.

353
00:17:43,853 --> 00:17:45,338
- Yeah.
- None. That...

354
00:17:45,424 --> 00:17:47,658
No. This is where
it gets really good.

355
00:17:47,767 --> 00:17:51,238
If you go on the hard shoulder
to overtake, the emergency lane,

356
00:17:51,304 --> 00:17:55,608
that's also one point
but only a 90 euro fine.

357
00:17:55,845 --> 00:17:58,486
There's your answer.
That's what you do!

358
00:17:59,103 --> 00:18:01,174
No, no.

359
00:18:03,127 --> 00:18:06,752
No, because... Aha.
You may think that.

360
00:18:06,799 --> 00:18:09,072
But if you fit your car
with blue lights,

361
00:18:09,189 --> 00:18:10,853
flashing blue lights, basically,

362
00:18:10,939 --> 00:18:12,908
you turn you car
into a police car,

363
00:18:13,010 --> 00:18:15,931
you get... I've got
the point fines here.

364
00:18:16,040 --> 00:18:18,580
20 Euro fine
and no points at all!

365
00:18:18,631 --> 00:18:21,513
What? You're joking!

366
00:18:22,751 --> 00:18:26,970
- No, you don't understand.
- That is true.

367
00:18:27,251 --> 00:18:29,244
That is very strange
to our ears.

368
00:18:29,330 --> 00:18:32,126
Cos if you tried that
at home in the UK,

369
00:18:32,244 --> 00:18:33,447
you would be charged with

370
00:18:33,509 --> 00:18:35,016
- impersonating a police officer,
- You understand...

371
00:18:35,040 --> 00:18:37,540
and you would never
get out of prison, ever.

372
00:18:37,603 --> 00:18:40,681
No, to me, people say Germans
have no sense of humour.

373
00:18:40,728 --> 00:18:42,751
If you want to know
what no sense of humour is,

374
00:18:42,822 --> 00:18:44,790
impersonate a policeman
in Britain.

375
00:18:44,892 --> 00:18:46,970
Then you'll know
what no sense of humour is.

376
00:18:47,087 --> 00:18:50,205
Right, that is the end
of Conversation Strasse.

377
00:18:54,306 --> 00:18:57,884
Now, we all like the idea of
a sports utility vehicle.

378
00:18:57,955 --> 00:19:00,845
A car that can handle the
Australian outback at the weekend

379
00:19:01,001 --> 00:19:05,011
and then set a new lap record at
Hockenheim on a Monday morning.

380
00:19:05,150 --> 00:19:07,447
But even the German
car-makers

381
00:19:07,555 --> 00:19:09,540
can't seem to make
the concept work.

382
00:19:09,565 --> 00:19:12,009
We've got this from Audi.
The RS Q3.

383
00:19:12,080 --> 00:19:13,837
Which is a dismal car.

384
00:19:14,033 --> 00:19:16,736
BMW have the X4,
I think that's called.

385
00:19:16,806 --> 00:19:17,931
Don't want one of those, either.

386
00:19:17,955 --> 00:19:20,509
Mercedes have
this horrible monster.

387
00:19:20,626 --> 00:19:22,775
So, they're all just rubbish.

388
00:19:22,869 --> 00:19:25,415
And let me guess.
You have a solution.

389
00:19:25,525 --> 00:19:26,699
- Yes, I do.
- Oh, God.

390
00:19:26,766 --> 00:19:28,665
Yes, I do. A car

391
00:19:28,751 --> 00:19:31,908
that is both sporty
and utilitarian.

392
00:19:32,033 --> 00:19:33,281
This will be good.

393
00:19:33,384 --> 00:19:35,939
Ye of little faith.
Watch this.

394
00:19:39,617 --> 00:19:41,758
This is a Land Rover Discovery

395
00:19:41,875 --> 00:19:43,650
doing utilitarian things

396
00:19:43,750 --> 00:19:46,531
in Britain's muddy underbelly.

397
00:19:49,172 --> 00:19:51,758
And obviously
a machine like this

398
00:19:51,789 --> 00:19:56,110
cannot possibly be
converted into a sports car.

399
00:19:58,726 --> 00:20:00,761
Or can it?

400
00:20:03,063 --> 00:20:07,016
First of all, we have to remove
this rather ungainly body.

401
00:20:07,094 --> 00:20:09,219
You can't do that
with a modern car

402
00:20:09,313 --> 00:20:12,336
because the body is the
chassis. It's the skeleton...

403
00:20:12,422 --> 00:20:15,227
If you take it away,
you're left with nothing more

404
00:20:15,399 --> 00:20:17,321
than a collection
of unjoined-up parts.

405
00:20:17,453 --> 00:20:19,492
However, you can remove the body

406
00:20:19,571 --> 00:20:20,899
on an old Discovery like this,

407
00:20:20,985 --> 00:20:24,250
using nothing more
than one of these.

408
00:20:30,989 --> 00:20:32,481
After just 40 minutes

409
00:20:32,583 --> 00:20:34,653
with no help from anyone else,

410
00:20:34,754 --> 00:20:37,762
I ended up with this.

411
00:20:43,402 --> 00:20:46,738
Obviously
it's still utilitarian.

412
00:20:46,872 --> 00:20:48,622
It will still wade
through rivers

413
00:20:48,700 --> 00:20:51,700
and... crawl its way
up muddy banks.

414
00:20:51,982 --> 00:20:53,575
But now there's a...

415
00:20:53,724 --> 00:20:55,904
a sporty flavour as well.

416
00:20:57,747 --> 00:21:02,732
Without the heavy body, it
feels nimble, agile, light.

417
00:21:06,529 --> 00:21:10,637
If it weren't for the fact that the
windscreen is now very close to my face,

418
00:21:11,044 --> 00:21:14,060
it would feel like
a Lamborghini Gallardo.

419
00:21:17,224 --> 00:21:19,036
The only real problem with this

420
00:21:19,061 --> 00:21:21,530
is that Britain
is a police state,

421
00:21:21,607 --> 00:21:23,365
and if I took this
on a public road,

422
00:21:23,430 --> 00:21:25,857
I'd be stopped immediately

423
00:21:26,029 --> 00:21:28,146
by the constabulary
who would point out

424
00:21:28,193 --> 00:21:30,372
that I was contravening about...

425
00:21:30,521 --> 00:21:34,200
4,870 different laws.

426
00:21:38,104 --> 00:21:40,232
It's not warm, either.

427
00:21:40,435 --> 00:21:42,552
Oh, no, that's stupid!

428
00:21:42,765 --> 00:21:45,364
Happily, both these
problems would be solved

429
00:21:45,426 --> 00:21:49,075
when I fitted it with
the body from a sports car.

430
00:21:51,848 --> 00:21:55,247
And this is the sports car
I've gone for.

431
00:21:56,629 --> 00:22:00,434
A 1978 MGB.

432
00:22:03,770 --> 00:22:06,684
Highly-trained men
are now removing its skin

433
00:22:06,754 --> 00:22:08,340
which will then be mated

434
00:22:08,440 --> 00:22:11,372
in a delicate two-hour
operation...

435
00:22:13,301 --> 00:22:14,967
to the internal organs

436
00:22:15,034 --> 00:22:17,379
of the mud-plugging V8.

437
00:22:18,872 --> 00:22:20,540
The following morning

438
00:22:20,739 --> 00:22:23,372
my incredible car was ready.

439
00:22:34,981 --> 00:22:36,325
It is incredible

440
00:22:36,489 --> 00:22:40,301
that in a shed I have created
something which has...

441
00:22:40,465 --> 00:22:44,715
eluded the combined might
of the motor industry.

442
00:22:45,036 --> 00:22:49,178
It is a proper
sports utility vehicle.

443
00:22:49,469 --> 00:22:51,241
I call it the MGD,

444
00:22:51,335 --> 00:22:53,647
and now I'm going to find out

445
00:22:53,708 --> 00:22:56,389
how well it works on a road.

446
00:23:06,476 --> 00:23:10,053
This is... magnificent.

447
00:23:12,405 --> 00:23:16,108
And it is quick. Oh, yeah.

448
00:23:17,904 --> 00:23:19,889
To demonstrate just how quick,

449
00:23:19,921 --> 00:23:21,499
I'm going to do a drag race

450
00:23:21,616 --> 00:23:23,655
against the motor
industry's idea

451
00:23:23,877 --> 00:23:25,553
of an SUV.

452
00:23:32,389 --> 00:23:33,968
Little bit of play there.

453
00:23:38,454 --> 00:23:40,456
Let's do this.

454
00:23:43,693 --> 00:23:46,530
Come on! Yes, look at this.

455
00:23:48,339 --> 00:23:50,875
The 1.5-litre diesel...

456
00:23:51,796 --> 00:23:57,034
is no match
for the 3.9-litre V8 MGD.

457
00:23:59,028 --> 00:24:01,894
Come on, Pride of Britain!

458
00:24:02,609 --> 00:24:04,877
Yes! Ha-ha-ha-ha-ha.

459
00:24:04,944 --> 00:24:08,142
Ah... ah... ah.

460
00:24:08,493 --> 00:24:10,118
Oh, God.

461
00:24:10,386 --> 00:24:12,588
The brakes don't work.

462
00:24:16,689 --> 00:24:18,829
With the performance box ticked,

463
00:24:18,970 --> 00:24:21,027
I continued my testing.

464
00:24:21,431 --> 00:24:25,298
In many ways,
the MGD puts me in mind

465
00:24:25,368 --> 00:24:27,618
of an Audi R8 Spyder.

466
00:24:28,665 --> 00:24:31,962
I mean, OK, in the Audi,
the dials would work.

467
00:24:32,118 --> 00:24:34,884
And the switches.
And the brakes.

468
00:24:35,275 --> 00:24:36,798
And the steering.

469
00:24:37,118 --> 00:24:39,353
And it's a bit less
bouncy, but...

470
00:24:39,603 --> 00:24:40,986
both of them

471
00:24:41,095 --> 00:24:43,642
are four-wheel-drive,
two-seater,

472
00:24:43,736 --> 00:24:46,418
drop-head V8s.

473
00:24:46,553 --> 00:24:48,603
There is, however,
one very big difference

474
00:24:48,743 --> 00:24:50,861
between the two cars.

475
00:24:51,204 --> 00:24:53,095
You can't do this in an Audi.

476
00:25:00,103 --> 00:25:02,835
Oh, yes. Yes.

477
00:25:03,298 --> 00:25:07,236
Moments ago I was haring
round a handling track,

478
00:25:07,299 --> 00:25:08,728
and now look.

479
00:25:09,341 --> 00:25:12,392
It's brilliant.

480
00:25:15,716 --> 00:25:19,192
Oh, no! Not now, you bastard.

481
00:25:19,309 --> 00:25:22,121
I mean, you wonderful thing.

482
00:25:22,505 --> 00:25:24,247
Choke. Oh.

483
00:25:24,880 --> 00:25:25,880
Yeah, that...

484
00:25:28,419 --> 00:25:30,567
It's on its shutdown thing.

485
00:25:30,754 --> 00:25:31,921
It's just to save fuel,

486
00:25:31,964 --> 00:25:34,286
it goes on two cylinders
sometimes.

487
00:25:36,770 --> 00:25:39,872
Once the engine management
thingy had run its...

488
00:25:40,052 --> 00:25:41,622
diagnostic program,

489
00:25:41,755 --> 00:25:43,770
I was back on the move.

490
00:25:44,249 --> 00:25:45,485
Here we go.

491
00:25:48,692 --> 00:25:50,082
Yes.

492
00:25:50,825 --> 00:25:54,253
Mighty four-wheel-drive
system hauling me up that.

493
00:25:54,320 --> 00:25:56,689
What the hell?

494
00:25:56,927 --> 00:25:59,645
Argh! Aargh!

495
00:26:00,044 --> 00:26:02,294
I'm stopping. Stopping.

496
00:26:05,231 --> 00:26:08,716
Oh, Lord,
that is not right, is it?

497
00:26:16,653 --> 00:26:18,552
As I got going
for the second time,

498
00:26:18,755 --> 00:26:21,325
I realised
I'd been a bit of a chump.

499
00:26:21,544 --> 00:26:22,849
The mistake I've made,
of course,

500
00:26:22,915 --> 00:26:25,755
is that I've... introduced
you to this car

501
00:26:25,825 --> 00:26:27,200
before I've really tested it.

502
00:26:27,255 --> 00:26:29,317
That's not
what car-makers do.

503
00:26:29,418 --> 00:26:31,449
They test a car and then show it

504
00:26:31,513 --> 00:26:34,239
to the... the press and the public.

505
00:26:34,614 --> 00:26:36,059
I'm doing that
the other way round.

506
00:26:36,145 --> 00:26:38,130
I'm introducing this to you

507
00:26:38,388 --> 00:26:40,317
before I've done
the testing and...

508
00:26:44,388 --> 00:26:46,763
Oh, for Christ's sake.

509
00:26:50,763 --> 00:26:52,856
You little beauty.

510
00:26:57,851 --> 00:27:01,208
Er, now, yes, what was I saying?

511
00:27:03,114 --> 00:27:07,638
I think the issue is really you're
watching my workings-out here.

512
00:27:08,427 --> 00:27:10,340
What you really want to see
is the finished product.

513
00:27:10,364 --> 00:27:12,198
That's what I should have done.

514
00:27:12,708 --> 00:27:15,239
Oh, Christ's sake.

515
00:27:17,263 --> 00:27:18,849
Right.

516
00:27:20,419 --> 00:27:23,411
At this point, I decided,
for no particular reason,

517
00:27:23,505 --> 00:27:25,712
to scrap the MG idea

518
00:27:25,849 --> 00:27:28,216
and go for
something else instead.

519
00:27:28,240 --> 00:27:31,356
♪♪

520
00:27:31,458 --> 00:27:33,731
This is what I chose.

521
00:27:33,833 --> 00:27:36,856
A 1980s Mercedes SL.

522
00:27:37,052 --> 00:27:39,286
Partly because
it's the very essence

523
00:27:39,427 --> 00:27:41,200
of quiet, urban restraint,

524
00:27:41,246 --> 00:27:42,847
taste and elegance.

525
00:27:42,981 --> 00:27:47,199
It's a car that was driven
by Bobby Ewing in Dallas.

526
00:27:47,442 --> 00:27:49,368
Mostly, though,
I chose it because

527
00:27:49,435 --> 00:27:53,114
it would fit more snugly
on the Discovery chassis.

528
00:27:56,270 --> 00:27:58,739
This time,
the men worked tirelessly

529
00:27:58,825 --> 00:28:00,184
for nearly a whole day

530
00:28:00,278 --> 00:28:01,700
to marry the two cars

531
00:28:01,849 --> 00:28:04,989
and the result... was spectacular.

532
00:28:09,013 --> 00:28:11,911
It's a car
I have justifiably called...

533
00:28:12,169 --> 00:28:14,093
The Excellent.

534
00:28:14,395 --> 00:28:17,474
The internal organs
from a Landrover Discovery

535
00:28:17,614 --> 00:28:22,802
mated to the beautiful skin
of a glamorous Mercedes SL.

536
00:28:23,278 --> 00:28:25,638
To create a vision of pure...

537
00:28:26,270 --> 00:28:27,567
What's the word?

538
00:28:27,708 --> 00:28:29,934
- OTHERS: Rubbish.
- It's not rubbish.

539
00:28:30,005 --> 00:28:33,192
Did you paint it
with a brush or a bucket?

540
00:28:33,317 --> 00:28:36,114
It's got those headlights that
swivel when you go round a bend.

541
00:28:36,169 --> 00:28:37,649
So they point at the road.

542
00:28:37,784 --> 00:28:39,606
OK, let me ask you this.

543
00:28:39,661 --> 00:28:40,927
Which would you rather have?

544
00:28:41,052 --> 00:28:43,083
The Excellent or that Porsche?

545
00:28:43,270 --> 00:28:45,224
BOTH: That Porsche.
- Why?

546
00:28:45,372 --> 00:28:47,994
Because it's better
in every single way.

547
00:28:48,302 --> 00:28:50,583
To prove my cynical
colleagues wrong,

548
00:28:50,669 --> 00:28:53,032
I invited them
to go for a drive.

549
00:28:55,316 --> 00:28:56,419
Oh, kind.

550
00:28:56,488 --> 00:28:59,605
See? It's an optional extra
for the shorter gentleman.

551
00:28:59,996 --> 00:29:02,418
- Are you comfy, Hammond?
- No.

552
00:29:02,652 --> 00:29:05,394
- Is this as in as I can get?
- Yep.

553
00:29:06,212 --> 00:29:09,305
- Woh!
- Right, listen to this.

554
00:29:11,239 --> 00:29:13,191
Oh, no, it moves!

555
00:29:17,019 --> 00:29:19,941
We'd only gone a few miles
before Richard and James

556
00:29:20,043 --> 00:29:21,808
completely changed their minds

557
00:29:21,902 --> 00:29:24,855
and realised that The
Excellent was the best car

558
00:29:25,019 --> 00:29:26,425
they'd ever been in.

559
00:29:26,573 --> 00:29:28,035
No, we haven't.
Stop saying things

560
00:29:28,082 --> 00:29:29,918
in voiceover that aren't true.

561
00:29:30,010 --> 00:29:31,200
I thought you'd
changed your mind.

562
00:29:31,224 --> 00:29:33,902
No! Maybe a bit.
It's worse than I thought.

563
00:29:34,113 --> 00:29:36,394
- Can I put the heater on?
- That's not connected.

564
00:29:36,601 --> 00:29:37,868
- Is it not?
- No.

565
00:29:37,942 --> 00:29:40,660
- What's that dial down there?
- Speedometer.

566
00:29:40,855 --> 00:29:42,425
Why have you got that one,
not that one?

567
00:29:42,550 --> 00:29:45,066
- That doesn't work.
- Has it got a fuel gauge?

568
00:29:45,277 --> 00:29:47,408
- Not as such.
- Has it got a temperature gauge?

569
00:29:47,433 --> 00:29:48,486
Not really.

570
00:29:48,511 --> 00:29:50,589
There's a lot of wires
hanging out of the dash

571
00:29:50,675 --> 00:29:51,955
that aren't connected to things.

572
00:29:51,991 --> 00:29:54,496
You haven't given it
an interior.

573
00:29:57,294 --> 00:29:59,847
- I can see the road.
- I can as well.

574
00:29:59,878 --> 00:30:02,800
No, there's a hole in the floor.

575
00:30:03,480 --> 00:30:06,527
While Hammond and May had
one or two minor issues,

576
00:30:06,605 --> 00:30:10,152
they both agreed that if I were
to put my car into production,

577
00:30:10,285 --> 00:30:12,511
it would make me a fortune.

578
00:30:12,589 --> 00:30:15,003
No, we didn't agree
to that, either.

579
00:30:15,160 --> 00:30:16,996
Look, I've
done the maths. Honestly.

580
00:30:17,121 --> 00:30:18,902
The Discovery was £2,500.

581
00:30:19,043 --> 00:30:22,433
Mercedes £4,500.
£7,000 for the work.

582
00:30:22,535 --> 00:30:26,418
That's 14,000 quid. I could
sell this for £120,000.

583
00:30:26,636 --> 00:30:28,127
- No, you couldn't.
- Yes, I could.

584
00:30:28,152 --> 00:30:30,222
A Cayenne Turbo is 120.

585
00:30:30,371 --> 00:30:34,207
A Cayenne Turbo is a proper
car built by Porsche.

586
00:30:34,332 --> 00:30:37,803
This is two scrap cars
glued together by a Muppet.

587
00:30:37,996 --> 00:30:40,128
It isn't designed
for people like you.

588
00:30:40,284 --> 00:30:42,370
What, people with eyes?

589
00:30:42,566 --> 00:30:44,464
People who can dress
themselves in the morning?

590
00:30:44,527 --> 00:30:47,378
I'll tell you exactly
who will buy this car.

591
00:30:47,449 --> 00:30:50,050
People who use
roundy-ended scissors.

592
00:30:50,160 --> 00:30:51,510
Footballers.

593
00:30:51,535 --> 00:30:53,753
- No, they won't.
- Footballers like Ferraris.

594
00:30:53,871 --> 00:30:55,566
Yeah, and Bentleys
and Range Rovers.

595
00:30:55,699 --> 00:30:58,113
- And Aston Martins.
- Not this thing.

596
00:31:03,229 --> 00:31:05,433
To prove them wrong again,

597
00:31:05,519 --> 00:31:10,097
I decided to head for the
nearby Chelsea training ground.

598
00:31:10,972 --> 00:31:14,105
These are people who understand
cars, not like you two.

599
00:31:14,222 --> 00:31:16,331
Yeah, they understand
cars, that's why they buy

600
00:31:16,355 --> 00:31:18,660
Range Rovers and Aston Martins.

601
00:31:18,800 --> 00:31:19,955
They buy those things

602
00:31:19,979 --> 00:31:22,472
cos they didn't know
that you could do this.

603
00:31:22,652 --> 00:31:25,089
- I like my car.
- It's shit.

604
00:31:30,488 --> 00:31:32,238
They're flocking to it,
aren't they?

605
00:31:32,371 --> 00:31:33,959
- You just watch.
- Do you mind

606
00:31:33,960 --> 00:31:37,363
if I go and stand
next to something else?

607
00:31:37,808 --> 00:31:39,496
Soon some players arrived,

608
00:31:39,628 --> 00:31:41,633
which gave Richard
and James a chance

609
00:31:41,746 --> 00:31:44,183
to show off their
footballing knowledge.

610
00:31:44,357 --> 00:31:46,425
You're really tall.
You should play in goal.

611
00:31:46,511 --> 00:31:47,777
Yeah, I do, I play in goal.

612
00:31:47,863 --> 00:31:49,136
- I'm the goalkeeper.
- I know that.

613
00:31:49,160 --> 00:31:51,050
What part of Chelsea
are you from?

614
00:31:51,207 --> 00:31:54,316
- I'm from Belgium.
- Oh.

615
00:31:54,746 --> 00:31:56,480
How do you know
they're footballers?

616
00:31:56,737 --> 00:31:58,207
Well, do you not recognise them?

617
00:31:58,425 --> 00:31:59,878
They're in football outfits...

618
00:31:59,971 --> 00:32:01,174
He doesn't recognise you.

619
00:32:01,394 --> 00:32:03,175
Where's...
Where's Alex Ferguson?

620
00:32:03,246 --> 00:32:05,391
Why don't we ask him?

621
00:32:05,839 --> 00:32:08,675
At this point I dismissed
my ignorant colleagues

622
00:32:08,816 --> 00:32:11,663
so that I could operate
the subtitle machine.

623
00:32:11,730 --> 00:32:13,665
(HE SPEAKS FRENCH)

624
00:32:24,180 --> 00:32:26,482
- Can you do keepy-uppy?
- Yeah.

625
00:32:27,923 --> 00:32:29,481
Take a shot at me.

626
00:32:30,493 --> 00:32:31,859
Well, that's ridiculous.
What can I do with that?

627
00:32:31,883 --> 00:32:33,665
You're supposed to jump.

628
00:32:36,525 --> 00:32:38,126
Flipping horrific.

629
00:32:38,251 --> 00:32:41,032
So you've butchered
a classic car?

630
00:32:41,423 --> 00:32:44,150
Right, watch this.
Little toss...

631
00:32:45,790 --> 00:32:46,798
No.

632
00:32:46,823 --> 00:32:48,868
You need to think of...

633
00:33:04,577 --> 00:33:06,327
- Ow.
- Saved.

634
00:33:06,497 --> 00:33:08,983
(HE SPEAKS PORTUGUESE)

635
00:33:12,959 --> 00:33:14,186
Having established

636
00:33:14,195 --> 00:33:17,397
that all top professional
footballers loved my car,

637
00:33:17,580 --> 00:33:19,682
we got back on the road.

638
00:33:21,900 --> 00:33:23,169
Did you get any orders?

639
00:33:23,413 --> 00:33:24,694
I noticed that the car park

640
00:33:24,725 --> 00:33:26,311
was still full of
Mercedes G-Class.

641
00:33:26,344 --> 00:33:28,632
- I saw that... Listen.
- Yeah.

642
00:33:29,038 --> 00:33:31,639
I could put this...
into an auction,

643
00:33:31,671 --> 00:33:33,608
one of those Posh,
up-market ones,

644
00:33:33,843 --> 00:33:35,882
and it would sell for £120,000.

645
00:33:36,116 --> 00:33:38,030
- It would not!
- Aah! Aah!

646
00:33:38,155 --> 00:33:40,803
To prove them wrong again...

647
00:33:40,923 --> 00:33:43,428
(LIVELY CLASSICAL MUSIC)

648
00:33:43,452 --> 00:33:47,280
♪♪

649
00:33:47,386 --> 00:33:51,223
♪♪

650
00:33:54,358 --> 00:33:57,718
Gentlemen,
people are examining...

651
00:33:57,843 --> 00:33:59,616
Yeah, they are the organisers.

652
00:33:59,725 --> 00:34:02,374
They're wondering
about their carpet.

653
00:34:03,577 --> 00:34:06,335
"Handcrafted by a renowned
British atelier...

654
00:34:06,436 --> 00:34:09,132
sympathetically marries
the chassis with..."

655
00:34:10,780 --> 00:34:14,007
- Did you write this?
- Course I wrote it.

656
00:34:14,358 --> 00:34:17,249
"The interior would benefit
from some minor attention."

657
00:34:17,350 --> 00:34:18,952
- Well, it would.
- With a hand grenade.

658
00:34:19,046 --> 00:34:20,522
Lot number 132.

659
00:34:20,577 --> 00:34:22,780
Soon the auction was under way.

660
00:34:22,952 --> 00:34:27,882
Ferrari 308 GTB, at £118,000.

661
00:34:28,249 --> 00:34:31,999
Lot number 127, start me
with this at 300,000.

662
00:34:32,093 --> 00:34:34,036
And many of the punters
were happy

663
00:34:34,061 --> 00:34:37,909
to pay six-figure sums
for the cars on offer.

664
00:34:38,139 --> 00:34:39,878
At 270,000.

665
00:34:39,945 --> 00:34:43,061
285 for the Countach.

666
00:34:43,499 --> 00:34:46,632
The Countach
just went for £285,000.

667
00:34:47,130 --> 00:34:48,402
I think I'm gonna sell...

668
00:34:48,454 --> 00:34:50,164
The Excellent for more than that.

669
00:34:50,600 --> 00:34:52,491
And then it was time.

670
00:34:52,671 --> 00:34:56,225
Moving on to lot number 138A.

671
00:34:56,452 --> 00:34:57,710
The Excellent.

672
00:34:57,757 --> 00:34:59,889
It's a fantastic handcrafted,

673
00:35:00,038 --> 00:35:02,085
very unusual machine,
as you can see.

674
00:35:02,178 --> 00:35:03,116
I don't want you...

675
00:35:03,169 --> 00:35:06,632
Beautiful, stylish
Mercedes Benz coachwork.

676
00:35:06,751 --> 00:35:09,520
- Very unusual, unique...
- Unusual?

677
00:35:09,588 --> 00:35:12,038
Here for sale this afternoon.

678
00:35:12,553 --> 00:35:14,946
Start me
if you will on this at...

679
00:35:15,077 --> 00:35:17,382
£425.

680
00:35:17,546 --> 00:35:19,251
At £425...

681
00:35:19,318 --> 00:35:21,225
Any advance at 400?

682
00:35:21,397 --> 00:35:22,811
£500. 550 anywhere?

683
00:35:22,873 --> 00:35:25,632
- Somebody's bid?
- 600 here.

684
00:35:25,686 --> 00:35:27,764
650. 650. 700 now.

685
00:35:27,882 --> 00:35:29,528
We're rattling up.

686
00:35:29,595 --> 00:35:33,222
AUCTIONEER:
700 here. 700. 800 now.

687
00:35:33,378 --> 00:35:34,933
Let's go for 1,000.

688
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:37,203
(SILENCE)

689
00:35:40,475 --> 00:35:42,743
Let's get going.
Come on, let's sell this car.

690
00:35:44,710 --> 00:35:46,678
- £1,000 here on my right.
- Are you bidding?

691
00:35:46,745 --> 00:35:48,640
- No.
- Jeremy, are you bidding?

692
00:35:49,616 --> 00:35:50,904
AUCTIONEER:
2,000 if you wish.

693
00:35:50,929 --> 00:35:53,398
It's 2,000 and five.
Two, five.

694
00:35:53,491 --> 00:35:56,859
3,000 now. It's 3,000 here.
Three, five anywhere?

695
00:35:57,281 --> 00:35:58,937
Three, one.

696
00:35:59,546 --> 00:36:01,023
At 3,100.

697
00:36:01,048 --> 00:36:03,046
£3,200.

698
00:36:03,234 --> 00:36:04,843
At £3,500.

699
00:36:04,890 --> 00:36:07,491
- It cost me 14,000.
- 4,000.

700
00:36:07,656 --> 00:36:09,593
At £4,000...

701
00:36:09,671 --> 00:36:11,537
At £4,000, any more?

702
00:36:11,603 --> 00:36:12,904
(SILENCE)

703
00:36:16,141 --> 00:36:17,867
At £4,000.

704
00:36:18,016 --> 00:36:19,445
Come and see us after.

705
00:36:19,511 --> 00:36:21,347
You just lost ten grand.

706
00:36:21,633 --> 00:36:23,969
He could have just
thrown it down the lavatory.

707
00:36:36,046 --> 00:36:37,748
It was rubbish.

708
00:36:38,312 --> 00:36:40,375
Hold on.

709
00:36:40,961 --> 00:36:43,797
You were bidding on your own car.

710
00:36:44,008 --> 00:36:46,570
Well, a bit. I just wanted
to get the ball rolling.

711
00:36:46,687 --> 00:36:48,008
But even then it didn't work

712
00:36:48,078 --> 00:36:49,975
because you only sold it
for four grand.

713
00:36:50,041 --> 00:36:51,492
It cost you 14,000 to make

714
00:36:51,569 --> 00:36:54,992
so you cost our production
company £10,000.

715
00:36:55,125 --> 00:36:56,726
No, no, not true.

716
00:36:56,766 --> 00:36:59,156
- I put a reserve on it.
- What reserve?

717
00:36:59,234 --> 00:37:00,992
£100,000.

718
00:37:01,531 --> 00:37:03,922
- £100,000?
- So it didn't sell at all,

719
00:37:03,976 --> 00:37:06,346
which means you cost us £14,000?

720
00:37:06,758 --> 00:37:10,570
Well, yes, but we've
ended up with The Excellent.

721
00:37:10,695 --> 00:37:14,366
No, we're stuck
with The Excellent.

722
00:37:14,633 --> 00:37:16,836
It's really difficult to
know, working with you,

723
00:37:16,930 --> 00:37:19,211
things like this, is it ambition

724
00:37:19,305 --> 00:37:21,773
or are you a lunatic?

725
00:37:22,273 --> 00:37:24,656
Sadly there isn't time
to answer that question,

726
00:37:24,789 --> 00:37:28,875
because it's time to play
Celebrity Brain Crash.

727
00:37:36,547 --> 00:37:38,711
Our guest this week
is a local girl

728
00:37:39,078 --> 00:37:43,281
who is responsible for one of my
all-time favourite pop songs,

729
00:37:43,453 --> 00:37:45,508
99 Red Balloons.

730
00:37:45,664 --> 00:37:47,516
She is a singer,

731
00:37:47,625 --> 00:37:49,891
she's an armpit hair enthusiast

732
00:37:49,976 --> 00:37:52,195
and she's
an all-round good sport.

733
00:37:52,273 --> 00:37:54,734
Ladies and gentlemen,
please welcome Nena!

734
00:38:14,833 --> 00:38:17,903
- Where is she?
- I've got no idea. Um...

735
00:38:19,185 --> 00:38:21,644
Oh. Oh, no...

736
00:38:22,011 --> 00:38:23,995
It's hard to see
through the smog,

737
00:38:24,081 --> 00:38:25,761
but yes, that is...

738
00:38:25,886 --> 00:38:28,800
- Oh, no.
- No. What's happened here is...

739
00:38:28,902 --> 00:38:30,175
Nena...

740
00:38:30,292 --> 00:38:33,511
yes, she's been
carried away by 99...

741
00:38:34,480 --> 00:38:37,248
- Red Ballons.
- Oh, no.

742
00:38:37,703 --> 00:38:39,170
Bad.

743
00:38:44,515 --> 00:38:46,468
Does that mean
she's not coming on, then?

744
00:38:46,804 --> 00:38:49,031
Well, James, she's floated
up into the stratosphere,

745
00:38:49,203 --> 00:38:52,429
her eyelids have frozen over
and her lungs are inside out.

746
00:38:52,562 --> 00:38:54,297
So that is a no.

747
00:38:54,750 --> 00:38:55,889
It's OK, though.

748
00:38:55,914 --> 00:38:58,695
We anticipated
that Nena may float away.

749
00:38:58,765 --> 00:39:01,703
- We have a back-up plan. We'll activate it.
- You sit down.

750
00:39:01,992 --> 00:39:05,148
You see, the thing is...
that more and more stuff,

751
00:39:05,203 --> 00:39:08,593
these days, is being powered
by rechargeable batteries.

752
00:39:08,672 --> 00:39:10,570
You know, phones, laptops.
That sort of thing.

753
00:39:10,625 --> 00:39:13,047
And this is giving the world
a bit of a problem.

754
00:39:13,133 --> 00:39:17,172
Because in Britain, our power
companies only produce

755
00:39:17,265 --> 00:39:20,625
five per cent more power
than we need.

756
00:39:20,718 --> 00:39:22,781
We're only just coping.

757
00:39:22,898 --> 00:39:25,461
It's actually worse
in the United States

758
00:39:25,500 --> 00:39:28,765
cos they produce 16% less
than they actually need,

759
00:39:28,851 --> 00:39:31,265
which means they have
to import electricity.

760
00:39:31,359 --> 00:39:33,945
So what is gonna happen
as more and more people

761
00:39:34,086 --> 00:39:36,601
are buying
and using electric cars?

762
00:39:36,718 --> 00:39:38,757
We're gonna need more power.
We may not be able to cope.

763
00:39:38,781 --> 00:39:40,711
No. I see the solution, you may think.

764
00:39:40,758 --> 00:39:42,508
It-Its is to build more power stations.

